:INFO
Shampoo Bar Troubleshooting
Most shampoo bar problems trace to lye calculation errors, cure time, or the wrong oil profile for the target hair type.

:PATH
Bars Leave Hair Greasy or Waxy
Superfat too high, insufficient cure time, or hard water interference.
|
:INFO
Bars Leave Hair Greasy or Waxy
Greasy result: superfat above 3% leaves conditioning oils on hair. Remake with 0 to 2% superfat. Waxy result: hard water reacts with soap (calcium and magnesium soap scum). Use a citric acid rinse (1/4 tsp in 1 cup water) after shampooing to break down soap film. Insufficient cure: bars used before 6 weeks are too soft and high in water content — the bar deposits excess water-soluble compounds.

:PATH
Bars Are Soft and Crumbly After 2 Weeks
Too much water in the formula or lye deficiency.
|
:INFO
Bars Are Soft and Crumbly After 2 Weeks
Water discount to 33% of oil weight produces a harder bar. Check your lye calculation — a low lye number produces a soft, greasy bar that never hardens. If bars are soft at 2 weeks but not greasy, they simply need more cure time. A bar that remains soft and slightly greasy at 6 weeks indicates a lye deficiency — do not use it.

:NOTE
Coconut Oil Percentage Affects Cleansing Harshness
Coconut oil above 50% to 60% of the formula produces a high-lather, highly cleansing bar that strips hair of natural oils and causes scalp irritation for many people. The formula above at 70% coconut is aggressive — reduce to 50 to 60% and increase olive oil for sensitive or dry scalps.
